{{Use British English|date=January 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}} {{Infobox civilian attack |title = 2004 Quetta Ashura massacre |image = Quetta.png |alt = |caption = |location = [[Quetta]], [[Balochistan (Pakistan)|Balochistan]], [[Pakistan]] |coordinates = |date = {{Start date|df=yes|2004|03|02}} |time = |timezone = |type = [[Grenade|Hand grenades]], [[Shooting]] and [[Rocket]]s |fatalities = 42 |injuries = at least 100 |perps = }} {{Hazara people}} {{Pakistan terrorist attacks}} The '''2004 Quetta Ashura massacre''' is the [[sectarian]] [[terrorist attack]] on Tuesday 2 March 2004 during an [[Day of Ashura|Ashura]] procession in southwestern city of [[Quetta]], in [[Balochistan, Pakistan|Balochistan]] province of [[Pakistan]]. At least 42 persons were killed and more than 100 wounded in the attack.<ref name="BBCnews11">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3524851.stm |title=South Asia &#124; Carnage in Pakistan Shia attack |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2 March 2004 |accessdate=23 May 2012 |archivedate=28 December 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228103841/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3524851.stm |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> The attack took place in Liaqat [[Bazaar]] Quetta, almost all of the victims were from [[Hazara people|Hazara]] ethnic minority of Balochistan. The incident occurred just after the incident of [[Iraq Ashura bombings|Karbala Ashura bombings]] in [[Iraq]].
==Background== The [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Muslim|Muslim's]] processions are held throughout [[List of Muslim-majority countries|world]] to commemorate the [[Shahid|martyrdom]] of [[Hussein ibn Ali|Imam Hussain Ibn Ali]] every year on the [[Day of Ashura]].<ref name="BBCnews11"/> Like other parts of [[Pakistan]], [[Quetta]] city has a notable population of Shia Muslims who mainly belong to [[Hazara people|Hazara community]]. In Quetta, the Ashura procession starts from [[Mehr Abad|Alamdar Road]], where all the [[Hussainia|Imambargahs]] gather from around the city mainly from [[Hazara Town]], then the procession moves to Mezan Chowk, where [[Ibadah|prayers]] are offered, and [[Mourning of Muharram|Matam]] was performed then moves to Liaqat Bazaar and ends on Alamdar Road.
==Massacre== The [[Day of Ashura|Ashura]] procession was on its traditional route, when it reached the main [[Bazaar]], three terrorist from top a building, threw [[Grenade|hand grenades]] followed by firing with automatic weapons before they blew themselves up, which left around 50 dead and more 100 injured.<ref name="BBCnews11"/><ref>Global Terrorism, By: Leonard Weinberg. p 213. Published 2009 by The Rosen Publishing Group Inc. NY</ref><ref name="autogenerated2">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3527697.stm |title=South Asia &#124; Pakistan probes assault on Shias |work=BBC News |date=3 March 2004 |accessdate=23 May 2012 |archivedate=23 November 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123174922/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3527697.stm |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref>
===Perpetrators=== The police identified the assailants bodies after DNA tests and investigations. They belonged to [[Lashkar-e-Jhangvi|Lashkar-e-Jhangvi (LeJ)]], the banned [[Pakistani]] [[terrorist group]]. The [[Balochistan Police|Police]] arrested a police constable who allegedly allowed the terrorist to use his house to plan the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_17-5-2004_pg7_10 |title=Leading News Resource of Pakistan |newspaper=[[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]] |date=17 May 2004 |accessdate=23 May 2012 |archivedate=12 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212205311/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_17-5-2004_pg7_10 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref>
==Funeral== A mass funeral was arranged the next day.<ref name="autogenerated2"/>
==Response and reactions== [[United Nations]] Secretary General [[Kofi Annan]] condemned the attacks and named it a ''cowardly'' act.<ref name="DawnNews">{{cite news|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2004/03/04/top16.htm |title=Ashura day attacks condemned world wide |newspaper=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn News]] |date=4 March 2004 |accessdate=23 May 2012 |archivedate=24 November 2011 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111124005958/http://archives.dawn.com/2004/03/04/top16.htm |df=dmy }}</ref>
The, Secretary-General of [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC)]], Abdulwahed Belkeziz said<ref name="DawnNews"/> {{quote|''Such terrorist acts can only be designed to incite sectarian (Sunni-Shia) strife and infighting among Muslims and to shed their blood.''}}
The Embassy of Japan in [[Islamabad]] issued a press release<ref name="DawnNews"/> {{quote|''Japan is deeply shocked and angered by the terrorist bombings in Baghdad and Karbala, Iraq, and the attacks in Quetta that occurred on Tuesday, causing many deaths and injuries. Terrorism cannot be justified on any account. Japan reiterates its firm condemnation of brutal terrorist attacks, which victimize the innocent. I extend my heartfelt condolences to the victims and the bereaved and wish the injured will have a speedy recovery.}}
[[Ministry of Interior (Pakistan)|Interior Minister of Pakistan]], [[Faisal Saleh Hayat]] condemned the attack and said<ref name="autogenerated2"/> {{quote|''These misguided extremists want to create chaos in the country.''}}
