{{other uses|Tablet (disambiguation)}} {{Cleanup rewrite|date=May 2009}} {{Refimprove|date=October 2006}}
A '''tablet''', in a religious context, is a term used for certain [[religious text]]s.
==In the Hebrew Bible== {{main|Tablets of Stone}} Judaism and Christianity maintain that [[Moses]] brought the [[Ten Commandments]] down from [[Mount Sinai]] in the form of two tablets of stone. According to the [[Book of Exodus]], God delivered the tablets twice, the first set having been smashed by Moses in his anger at the idol-worship of the Israelites.
==In Islam== The Preserved Tablet (''al-Lawhu 'l-Mahfuz''), the heavenly preserved record of all that has happened and will happen, contains ''[[Predestination in Islam|qadar]]''. ''Qadar'' ({{lang-ar|قدر}}, [[Hans Wehr transliteration|transliterated]] ''qadar'', meaning "fate", "divine fore-ordainment", "predestination")<ref name="Wehr">J. M. Cowan (ed.) (1976). ''The Hans Wehr Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic''. Wiesbaden, Germany: Spoken Language Services. {{ISBN|0-87950-001-8}}</ref> is the concept of [[Divinity|divine]] [[destiny]] in [[Islam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missionislam.com/knowledge/Qadar.htm|title=Qadar|work=missionislam.com}}</ref>
== In the Bahá'í Faith== The term "tablet" is part of the title of many shorter [[Bahá'í literature|works]] of [[Bahá'u'lláh]], founder of the [[Bahá'í Faith]], and his son and successor [[`Abdu'l-Bahá]].<ref name="iranica">{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia= Encyclopædia Iranica |year= 2005|article=Lawhḥ| first1 = Moojan | last1 = Momen | authorlink= Moojan Momen | author2 = Lawson, B.T. | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/lawh }}</ref>
